{{Infobox Artwork | alt= | image_file=Munch, Weihnachten im Bordell (1904).jpg | image_size=220px | title=Christmas in the Brothel | other_language_1=Norwegian | other_title_1=Julaften i bordell | artist=[[Edvard Munch]] | year=1903–04 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil]] on [[canvas]] | height_metric=60 | width_metric=88 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=Oslo | museum=[[Munch Museum]] }}
'''''Christmas in the Brothel''''' ({{lang-no|'''Julaften i bordell'''}}) is an oil-on-canvas painting by Norwegian painter [[Edvard Munch]]. The Expressionist painting was completed in 1903–04 and is housed at the [[Munch Museum]] in Oslo.
==Background== The painting was done at a difficult time for Munch: a commission for a portrait in Hamburg (of a Senator Holthusen, the father in law of Munch's patron [[Max Linde]]) had come to naught because of disagreements. As a result, Munch suffered anxieties, which he attempted to manage with alcohol. A visit to a brothel in Lübeck is supposedly the background to ''Christmas in the Brothel'', a "light yet melancholy" painting in which the working girls in a brothel have just finished decorating a Christmas tree. "Ironic, sentimentally unholy", the painting is interpreted as a commentary on both Linde's upper-class household (where Munch was staying at the time) and Munch's own "pietistic home background".<ref name="Bischoff2000">{{cite book|last=Bischoff|first=Ultich|title=Edvard Munch, 1863–1944|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ETahibk334cC&pg=PA74|accessdate=9 April 2013|year=2000|publisher=Taschen|isbn=9783822859711|page=74}}</ref> Like other paintings of the period, it shows Munch's association with [[Fauvism]].<ref name="Clement1994">{{cite book|last=Clement|first=Russell T|title=Les Fauves: a sourcebook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VcaMyvjUZhIC&pg=PA73|accessdate=9 April 2013|year=1994|publisher=Greenwood|isbn=9780313283338|page=73}}</ref> Prostitution was a favored topic of Munch's, and one particular room in a German brothel would later inspire an entire series of paintings, ''The Green Room''.<ref name="Ringdal2007">{{cite book|last=Ringdal|first=Nils Johan|title=Love for Sale: A World History of Prostitution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bYTW_eUOAesC&pg=PA251|accessdate=9 April 2013|year=2007|publisher=Grove|isbn=9781555848088|page=251}}</ref>
